Security Policy
The aiOut project is built on the philosophy that true security cannot be "granted" by a service provider; it must be architected into the hardware and code you control.

Zero-Telemetry & Local-Only
aiOut operates on a Local-First security model.

No "Phone Home": The agent does not send usage logs, crash reports, or telemetry to any central server. All diagnostics remain on your device.

Encrypted Storage: All biometric keys and configuration data are stored in your device’s hardware-backed Secure Enclave (TPM/TEE). They never touch the network in a readable format.

Verification-Based: We do not rely on "trusted" third-party certificates. We rely on cryptographic proofs verified on the Solana blockchain and stored on the Arweave permaweb.

Reporting Vulnerabilities
Because aiOut is open-source and decentralized, security is a community responsibility. If you identify a vulnerability or a logic flaw:

Inspect: Please review the /kernel (eBPF/XDP logic) and /agent (signing logic) directories to verify the source of the issue.

Open an Issue: Open a public issue in this repository. Transparency is our first line of defense against the "cluster buck" of proprietary software.

Submit a Fix: Since this is a community-owned protocol, we encourage "pull requests" that harden the code. If your fix improves the security of the Consent Stack, it will be merged into the master branch.

Hardening the Circuit
We are specifically focused on mitigating the following threat vectors:

Scraper/Bot Ingress: Managed at the kernel level via XDP.

Identity Impersonation: Prevented via biometric WebAuthn ceremonies bound to device-specific SNS handles.

Protocol Injection: Prevented via cryptographic signing of all manifest updates.

What is NOT Covered
aiOut provides the infrastructure for you to secure your device. We are not a "cloud security" service. We provide the tools for you to air-gap your intent from the intrusive corporate web. You are responsible for the physical security of your hardware and the management of your local cryptographic keys.

If you don't trust the code, fork it and rewrite it. That is the aiOut way.
